00:09:05.166 --> 00:09:07.040
JACOB SOVIERO: So I'd
like to actually start.

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:09.039
We saw that a little bit
in the end in the film.

00:09:09.039 --> 00:09:12.140
We talked about PTSD and
moral injury, moral dilemma,

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:13.852
and the difference
between the two.

00:09:13.852 --> 00:09:16.310
I'm having, Dr. Maguen, could
you tell us a little bit more

00:09:16.310 --> 00:09:20.450
about the relationship
between PTSD and moral injury?

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:21.700
SHIRA MAGUEN: Absolutely.

00:09:24.780 --> 00:09:26.460
Absolutely.

00:09:26.460 --> 00:09:30.120
Well, first, I want
to just say that I

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:32.535
think PTSD is more
of a diagnosis,

00:09:32.535 --> 00:09:35.610
so that's really
important to recognize,

00:09:35.610 --> 00:09:38.790
whereas moral injury is more
something that we think about

00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:39.670
on a continuum.

00:09:39.670 --> 00:09:42.630
It's a problem that
people face, but one

00:09:42.630 --> 00:09:44.550
that is not a diagnosis.

00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:46.980
And as we saw in the
film, it's really

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:50.880
about feeling like you
crossed over some line that

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:52.290
goes against your--

00:09:52.290 --> 00:09:55.200
that you went against your own
moral beliefs and expectations

00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:57.540
and that, as a
result, you're really

00:09:57.540 --> 00:10:00.920
having some struggles or some
inner conflict in relation

00:10:00.920 --> 00:10:01.420
to that.

00:10:01.420 --> 00:10:05.100
So when we think
about PTSD, PTSD

00:10:05.100 --> 00:10:07.720
is really made up of
several different symptoms.

00:10:07.720 --> 00:10:10.590
And so with PTSD,
you really think

00:10:10.590 --> 00:10:13.650
about a person having
re-experiencing symptoms,

00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:16.410
meaning they're having
nightmares or dreams about what

00:10:16.410 --> 00:10:18.520
happened to them as an example.

00:10:18.520 --> 00:10:23.520
They also avoid in a
great respect reminders

00:10:23.520 --> 00:10:27.840
of what happened to them while
they were deployed, reminders

00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:30.910
of the emotional experience
that they might have felt,

00:10:30.910 --> 00:10:34.140
so if they felt fear
or guilt or shame,

00:10:34.140 --> 00:10:36.220
they try to avoid
those emotions as well.

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:39.540
And then, the third
part of PTSD is arousal,

00:10:39.540 --> 00:10:43.260
and so you saw in the
film that difficulty

00:10:43.260 --> 00:10:48.030
with anger or difficulty falling
asleep or feeling like you

00:10:48.030 --> 00:10:52.790
were just on constant alert or
that you were easily startled.

00:10:52.790 --> 00:10:57.150
And so those three pieces
really make up PTSD.

00:10:57.150 --> 00:11:00.150
In addition to that,
people also sometimes

00:11:00.150 --> 00:11:02.920
have thoughts
about what they did

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:07.320
or what they experience that can
cause them to really feel down

00:11:07.320 --> 00:11:09.330
or to want to isolate.

00:11:09.330 --> 00:11:11.820
With moral injury,
again, the idea

00:11:11.820 --> 00:11:16.110
is that you have crossed some
line and that as a result,

00:11:16.110 --> 00:11:20.640
really, you feel some deep guilt
and some deep shame, possibly,

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:22.950
and also some isolation.

00:11:22.950 --> 00:11:26.280
And in addition to
that, there is a failure

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:29.290
to be able to forgive
yourself for what you did.

00:11:29.290 --> 00:11:32.160
And so I think that that was
really very nicely highlighted

00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:35.430
in the film that the
struggle was really

00:11:35.430 --> 00:11:39.390
with how you saw yourself
as a person and a struggle

00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:43.590
with the failure to forgive,
and once that was tackled,

00:11:43.590 --> 00:11:47.377
it really helped the person
to cross that line and heal.

00:11:47.377 --> 00:11:49.710
And in many cases, we see
that with many of the veterans

00:11:49.710 --> 00:11:51.302
that we work with as well.

00:11:51.302 --> 00:11:53.760
And so I think that, really,
if we think about it as a Venn

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:58.110
diagram, you can have PTSD,
and you can have moral injury.

00:11:58.110 --> 00:12:00.870
And those things do
have a lot of overlap,

00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:03.870
but you can also have
PTSD without moral injury

00:12:03.870 --> 00:12:06.480
and moral injury
without PTSD as well.

00:12:06.480 --> 00:12:11.010
And so I think that, again,
if we think about PTSD

00:12:11.010 --> 00:12:14.730
with really having PTSD as
a result of something that

00:12:14.730 --> 00:12:15.870
happened to you--

00:12:15.870 --> 00:12:19.020
being exposed to a lot of
IEDs, a lot of explosions,

00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:20.670
your body is on alert--

00:12:20.670 --> 00:12:22.650
that's more what
PTSD looks like.

00:12:22.650 --> 00:12:27.240
And moral injury is more about
guilt and shame and a failure

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:29.940
to forgive oneself that
can really lead to things

00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:34.020
that we saw in the film like
suicide, like sabotaging

00:12:34.020 --> 00:12:36.020
your relationships.

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:38.820
And sometimes that
inner conflict,

00:12:38.820 --> 00:12:40.500
that once you find
that inner peace,

00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:42.820
things can go very,
very differently.

00:12:42.820 --> 00:12:46.370
So hopefully, that helps
with clarifying the two

00:12:46.370 --> 00:12:48.270
to a little bit--
to a greater extent.

00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:50.070
JACOB SOVIERO:
